sources.name: Logistic Chaos
sources.description: The simplest chaotic system --- one-line recurrence x(n+1) = 4x(1-x) at r=4, filling the unit interval ergodically with a beta(½,½) distribution

sources.name: Henon Map
sources.description: Classic 2D chaotic map --- the strange attractor has fractal cross-sections and correlation dimension ~1.25, a benchmark for testing dimension estimators

sources.name: Tent Map
sources.description: Piecewise-linear chaos --- a V-shaped map near slope 2, producing uniform invariant density with maximal topological entropy

sources.name: Lorenz Attractor
sources.description: Lorenz '63 system x-coordinate --- the butterfly attractor, sensitive dependence on initial conditions. Two-lobe structure with unpredictable switching

sources.name: Rossler Attractor
sources.description: Rossler system x-coordinate --- the simplest 3D continuous chaotic flow, a single folded band with period-doubling route to chaos

sources.name: Prime Gaps
sources.description: Gaps between consecutive primes --- locally erratic but statistically governed by the prime number theorem, with conjectured connections to random matrix theory

sources.name: Collatz Trajectory
sources.description: Collatz trajectory mod 256, restarting from consecutive integers to avoid 4-2-1 cycle collapse

sources.name: Divisor Count
sources.description: Divisor count d(n) --- erratic arithmetic function averaging ~ln(n), spikes at highly composite numbers, modulated by prime factorization structure

sources.name: Pi Digits
sources.description: Digits of pi in base 256 --- conjectured normal (equidistributed), but entirely deterministic. Passes most statistical randomness tests

sources.name: White Noise
sources.description: IID uniform random bytes --- the null model, maximum entropy with zero sequential correlation

sources.name: Blue Noise
sources.description: High-pass filtered noise (PSD ~ f) --- anti-correlated increments that suppress low frequencies, common in error-diffusion dithering and spatial statistics

sources.name: Pink Noise
sources.description: 1/f noise (PSD ~ 1/f) --- equal energy per octave, ubiquitous in nature from heartbeat intervals to semiconductor flicker noise. Between white noise and Brownian motion

sources.name: Brownian Walk
sources.description: Cumulative sum of Gaussian increments --- the canonical random walk, self-affine with Hurst exponent H=0.5 and PSD ~ 1/f²

sources.name: fBm (Antipersistent)
sources.description: Fractional Brownian motion with H=0.3 --- antipersistent (trend-reversing), rougher than standard Brownian motion

sources.name: fBm (Persistent)
sources.description: Fractional Brownian motion with H=0.7 --- persistent (trend-following), smoother trajectories with long-range dependence

sources.name: ARMA(2,1)
sources.description: Autoregressive moving-average process --- linear short-memory dynamics, the workhorse model of classical time-series analysis

sources.name: Regime Switching
sources.description: Two-state hidden Markov process --- alternates between calm (σ=0.5) and volatile (σ=3.0) regimes with asymmetric transition rates

sources.name: Sine Wave
sources.description: Pure sinusoid --- perfectly periodic, single-frequency, minimal complexity. The baseline for all oscillatory comparisons

sources.name: Sawtooth Wave
sources.description: Sawtooth wave --- linear ramp with discontinuous reset, rich in harmonics (1/n Fourier decay)

sources.name: Linux ELF x86-64
sources.description: Stripped Linux x86-64 PIE executable (3.7 MB) --- ELF with .text, .rodata, relocation tables, and x86-64 instruction byte patterns

sources.name: OpenBSD ELF x86-64
sources.description: Stripped OpenBSD x86-64 PIE executable (1.1 MB) --- ELF with W^X enforcement, subtly different instruction mix from Linux due to compiler and ABI differences

sources.name: Windows PE x86-64
sources.description: Windows PE32+ console executable (2.3 MB) --- x86-64 with PE headers, import tables, and different code generation patterns from Unix compilers

sources.name: macOS Mach-O (dyld)
sources.description: macOS dyld universal binary (2.6 MB) --- i386 + x86-64 + arm64e __text sections, pure machine code

sources.name: AES Encrypted
sources.description: Simulated AES-CTR ciphertext --- keyed PRNG output indistinguishable from random without the key, the gold standard for pseudorandom streams

sources.name: Gzip (level 1)
sources.description: Gzip-compressed data (1.4 MB, level 1) --- fast DEFLATE with more residual structure

sources.name: Gzip (level 9)
sources.description: Gzip-compressed data (1.3 MB, level 9) --- maximum DEFLATE compression, near-entropy stream

sources.name: Bzip2 (level 1)
sources.description: Bzip2-compressed data (1.2 MB, level 1, 100k blocks) --- Burrows-Wheeler transform with small block size preserves more local structure from the original data

sources.name: Bzip2 (level 9)
sources.description: Bzip2-compressed data (1.1 MB, level 9, 900k blocks) --- BWT with maximum block size, approaching the entropy floor of the source data

sources.name: Devil's Staircase
sources.description: Cantor function --- continuous and monotone but with derivative zero almost everywhere. A singular measure concentrated on a fractal set of measure zero

sources.name: Levy Flight
sources.description: Random walk with Cauchy-distributed jumps --- infinite variance, occasional extreme leaps create fractal clustering of visited sites

sources.name: Thue-Morse
sources.description: Binary substitution sequence (0→01, 1→10) --- perfectly balanced yet aperiodic, with flat Fourier spectrum like random noise despite being entirely deterministic

sources.name: Fibonacci Word
sources.description: Sturmian sequence --- the simplest aperiodic word, with golden-ratio quasiperiodicity and complexity function p(n) = n + 1 (minimal for non-periodic sequences)

sources.name: Hilbert Walk
sources.description: 1D trace of Hilbert space-filling curve --- preserves 2D locality, creating structured self-similar fluctuations at every scale

sources.name: Random Steps
sources.description: Random piecewise-constant signal --- flat plateaus of random height with geometrically-distributed durations, creating a sparse derivative and blocky texture

sources.name: Weierstrass
sources.description: Weierstrass function --- continuous everywhere but differentiable nowhere, the first known mathematical 'monster'. Self-similar roughness at all scales

sources.name: Exponential Chirp
sources.description: Exponential frequency sweep --- instantaneous frequency grows geometrically, creating equal time per octave. Used in acoustic measurements and radar

sources.name: Baker Map
sources.description: Baker's map --- stretching and folding like kneading dough, the canonical model of chaotic mixing. Re-seeded every 40 iterations to avoid float collapse

sources.name: Chirikov Standard Map
sources.description: Chirikov standard map at K=0.9716 --- mixed phase space with coexisting regular islands and chaotic sea, the paradigm of Hamiltonian chaos

sources.name: Logistic Edge-of-Chaos
sources.description: Logistic map at the Feigenbaum point r=3.5699 --- the boundary between order and chaos, where the period-doubling cascade accumulates

sources.name: Logistic r=3.2 (Period-2)
sources.description: Logistic map in stable period-2 --- output alternates between two fixed values, the simplest oscillation after the first bifurcation

sources.name: Logistic r=3.5 (Period-4)
sources.description: Logistic map in period-4 --- four-value cycle after the second bifurcation, output concentrates on four narrow bands

sources.name: Logistic r=3.68 (Banded Chaos)
sources.description: Logistic map in banded chaos --- chaotic within disjoint bands that the orbit cycles through, mixing local unpredictability with global periodicity

sources.name: Logistic r=3.83 (Period-3 Window)
sources.description: Logistic map in the period-3 window --- a stable island inside the chaotic sea. By Sharkovskii's theorem, period-3 implies all periods exist nearby

sources.name: Logistic r=3.9 (Near-Full Chaos)
sources.description: Logistic map at r=3.9 --- nearly full chaos but with thin gaps in the attractor revealing remnants of periodic windows

sources.name: Critical Circle Map
sources.description: Sine circle map at K=1 critical coupling with golden-mean bare frequency --- sits on the boundary of mode-locking, a different universality class from Feigenbaum's period-doubling

sources.name: Perlin Noise
sources.description: Spectral Perlin-like noise --- coherent smooth fluctuations with 1/f amplitude falloff, widely used for procedural terrain and texture generation

sources.name: Square Wave
sources.description: Square wave --- binary oscillation (0 or 255), maximal harmonic content with 1/n odd-harmonic Fourier series

sources.name: Collatz Parity
sources.description: Collatz parity sequence --- binary trace (even/odd) of the 3n+1 orbit, conjectured to behave like a biased coin flip with P(odd) ≈ log₂(3)/(1+log₂(3))

sources.name: Collatz Stopping Times
sources.description: Collatz stopping times --- how many steps each integer takes to reach 1. Wildly erratic, with typical values around 3.5·log₂(n) but enormous outliers

sources.name: Mertens Function
sources.description: Cumulative sum of the Moebius function --- a random-walk-like sequence whose growth rate is equivalent to the Riemann Hypothesis (O(n^(½+ε)) iff RH)

sources.name: Euler Totient Ratio
sources.description: Euler totient ratio φ(n)/n --- the fraction of integers below n that are coprime to n, dense in (0,1) with a fractal structure governed by prime factorization

sources.name: RANDU
sources.description: IBM's infamous RANDU (1968) --- the worst widely-deployed RNG in history. Points fall on just 15 parallel planes in 3D. Multiplier 65539 = 2¹⁶+3

sources.name: glibc LCG
sources.description: The C standard library LCG --- used by glibc rand() for decades. Low bits cycle with short period, high bits have lattice structure in dimensions >5

sources.name: Middle-Square (von Neumann)
sources.description: Von Neumann's 1949 middle-square PRNG --- famously degenerates to short cycles. Square the state, extract middle digits. Exhibits visible lattice structure.

sources.name: Neural Net (Dense)
sources.description: Synthetic neural network weights --- Gaussian-initialized dense layer, resembling the near-random parameters of an untrained network

sources.name: Neural Net (Pruned 90%)
sources.description: Pruned neural network weights (90% zero) --- extreme sparsity typical of compressed models, creates a near-zero-dominated distribution with scattered non-zero entries

sources.name: Rule 30
sources.description: Wolfram Rule 30 center column --- produces output indistinguishable from random despite simple local rules. Used as Mathematica's default random generator

sources.name: Rule 110
sources.description: Wolfram Rule 110 center column --- proven Turing-complete, the simplest known universal computer. Supports gliders and localized structures like a 1D Game of Life

sources.name: Gaussian Noise
sources.description: Gaussian noise scaled to fill uint8 --- bell-curve density with 3σ mapped to [0,255], concentrating samples around the midpoint

sources.name: Triangle Wave
sources.description: Triangle wave --- linear ramps up and down, smooth peaks with 1/n² Fourier decay (only odd harmonics)

sources.name: Dice Rolls
sources.description: Simulated dice rolls --- uniform over just 6 levels (0, 51, 102, 153, 204, 255), creating a maximally discrete distribution with IID independence

sources.name: Classical MIDI
sources.description: Real MIDI files --- Bach (chorale, Brandenburg 3), Beethoven (5th), Mozart (Figaro). Raw Standard MIDI format 1 bytes: delta-time VLQs, note-on/off events, multi-track. 365KB.

sources.name: Clipped Sine
sources.description: Sine wave hard-clipped at 70% --- flat tops and bottoms create a hybrid of smooth oscillation and constant segments, concentrating the distribution at extremes

sources.name: L-System (Algae)
sources.description: Lindenmayer system (A→AB, B→A) --- the simplest L-system, producing Fibonacci-length words. Deterministic, self-similar, with growth rate equal to the golden ratio

sources.name: Symbolic Lorenz
sources.description: Lorenz attractor reduced to a binary symbol stream (left lobe vs right lobe), one symbol per half-orbit. The symbolic itinerary encodes the topological structure of chaos

sources.name: Symbolic Henon
sources.description: Henon map reduced to a binary symbol stream (x < 0 or x > 0) --- the symbolic itinerary of a 2D strange attractor, encoding its topological horseshoe structure

sources.name: Human Proteome
sources.description: Real human proteome --- 20,431 reviewed Swiss-Prot sequences (UniProt 2025), raw ASCII bytes (20 amino acid letters in the 65-89 range). 11.4M residues.

sources.name: English Literature
sources.description: Real Project Gutenberg text --- Austen, Carroll, Doyle, Melville (2.8MB). Raw ASCII bytes with natural English letter frequencies and word structure.

sources.name: μ-law Sine
sources.description: Sine wave with non-linear mu-law quantization (G.711). Creates a structural bridge between analogue waves and discrete logic.

sources.name: Earthquake Magnitudes
sources.description: Real USGS earthquake magnitudes --- Gutenberg-Richter distribution, 8395 events (CORGIS/USGS)

sources.name: Earthquake Depths
sources.description: Real USGS earthquake depths --- bimodal: shallow crustal (<30km) and deep subduction (>100km)

sources.name: Earthquake Intervals
sources.description: Real USGS interevent times --- Omori-law clustering after mainshocks, Poisson background (CORGIS/USGS)

sources.name: El Centro 1940
sources.description: 1940 Imperial Valley NS strong motion --- the most-studied earthquake record in structural engineering

sources.name: Rainfall (ORD Hourly)
sources.description: Real hourly precipitation at Chicago O'Hare 2020--2023 (IEM/ASOS). 35k observations, ~85% zero (dry hours), heavy-tailed wet spells. Public domain.

sources.name: Ocean Wind (Buoy)

sources.name: Wave Height (Buoy)

sources.name: Barometric Pressure (Buoy)
sources.description: NOAA buoy 46042 atmospheric pressure --- real synoptic weather patterns, 10-min intervals (CC0)

sources.name: Geomagnetic ap Index
sources.description: Real 3-hourly geomagnetic ap index 1932-present --- solar-driven magnetic storms, 93 years (CC BY 4.0, GFZ)

sources.name: Potomac River Flow
sources.description: USGS gauge 01646500 --- real 15-min discharge, Potomac near DC, 2024 (public domain)

sources.name: Seismograph (ANMO)
sources.description: IRIS IU.ANMO broadband vertical --- real 40Hz seismograph, Albuquerque NM, 2024-01-01 (CC0)

sources.name: GOES X-Ray Flux
sources.description: GOES satellite 1-min X-ray flux --- solar flare monitoring, log-scale A/B/C/M/X classes (NOAA)

sources.name: Codon Usage
sources.description: Synthetic coding DNA --- nucleotide triplets (codons) with Zipf-like usage bias and weak Markov transitions, emitted as raw ASCII bases (A=65, C=67, G=71, T=84)

sources.name: Poker Hands
sources.description: Stream of poker hand ranks (High Card through Royal Flush) --- extremely skewed: ~50% High Card, ~42% Pair, <0.002% Straight Flush or better

sources.name: Pulse-Width Modulation
sources.description: Pulse-width modulation --- binary carrier (0/255) whose duty cycle sweeps smoothly via sine modulation, encoding an analog signal in digital on/off timing

sources.name: Morse Code
sources.description: Synthetic Morse code --- dots (1 unit), dashes (3 units), and hierarchical gaps (1/3/7 units). Creates multi-scale on/off structure encoding random letter sequences

sources.name: Sensor Event Stream
sources.description: Categorical sensor event stream --- door open/close, motion, temperature alerts with state-dependent transitions. Mostly quiet (value 0) with coupled event bursts

sources.name: Chua's Circuit
sources.description: Double-scroll electronic chaos --- bimodal attractor with different topology from Lorenz

sources.name: Double Pendulum
sources.description: Angular velocity of second arm --- mechanical chaos with mixed regular/chaotic regions

sources.name: Mackey-Glass
sources.description: Delay-differential equation modeling blood cell regulation --- high-dimensional chaos

sources.name: Surface Wind (ORD 5-min)
sources.description: Real 5-minute surface wind speed at Chicago O'Hare 2023 (IEM/ASOS). 114k observations, quantized to ~1-knot steps (31 levels). Captures gusts, diurnal cycles, and frontal passages. Public domain.

sources.name: Sandpile
sources.description: Bak-Tang-Wiesenfeld sandpile --- self-organized criticality produces power-law avalanche sizes without parameter tuning. Slow buildup with sudden cascading collapses

sources.name: Stochastic Resonance
sources.description: Weak periodic signal amplified by noise in a bistable potential --- intermittent well-hopping

sources.name: Coupled Map Lattice
sources.description: Spatiotemporal chaos in coupled logistic maps --- chimera states and coherence-incoherence patterns

sources.name: Kuramoto Oscillators
sources.description: Order parameter of coupled oscillators near synchronization transition --- partial coherence

sources.name: Van der Pol Oscillator
sources.description: Van der Pol relaxation oscillations --- slow drift along cubic nullcline punctuated by fast jumps, the canonical model of nonlinear self-sustained oscillation

sources.name: Fibonacci Quasicrystal
sources.description: 1D Fibonacci quasicrystal --- aperiodic tiling with long-range order, discrete diffraction

sources.name: Langton's Ant
sources.description: Multi-state turmite on small torus --- complex emergent trajectories from simple rules

sources.name: Continued Fractions
sources.description: CF digits of random quadratic irrationals --- bounded partial quotients with hidden periodicity

sources.name: Forest Fire
sources.description: Drossel-Schwabl forest fire model --- tree density fluctuates as growth and burns compete

sources.name: Duffing Oscillator
sources.description: Driven damped nonlinear oscillator --- strange attractor with broad amplitude visits

sources.name: Pomeau-Manneville
sources.description: Pomeau-Manneville type-I intermittency --- near a tangent bifurcation, the orbit lingers in long laminar phases before erupting into chaotic bursts. Power-law laminar length distribution

sources.name: Rudin-Shapiro
sources.description: Partial sums of Rudin-Shapiro --- deterministic random walk with flat spectral density

sources.name: De Bruijn Sequence
sources.description: B(4,4) De Bruijn cycle --- every 4-symbol window over alphabet 0-3 appears exactly once

sources.name: Champernowne
sources.description: Provably normal number in base 256 --- uniform digit distribution but deterministic concatenation

sources.name: Collatz Flights
sources.description: Peak altitude of Collatz orbits --- how high consecutive integers fly before crashing to 1

sources.name: Stern-Brocot Walk
sources.description: Stern diatomic sequence --- every positive rational visited once, fractal self-similar structure

sources.name: Random Telegraph
sources.description: Two-state Markov process with exponential holding times --- binary correlation structure

sources.name: Geometric Brownian Motion
sources.description: Geometric Brownian motion --- multiplicative random walk (dS/S = μdt + σdW), the basis of Black-Scholes option pricing. Log-normal distribution with positive skew

sources.name: Ornstein-Uhlenbeck
sources.description: Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process --- mean-reverting diffusion with stationary Gaussian distribution, the continuous-time analog of an AR(1) process. Bounded excursions unlike Brownian motion

sources.name: Beta Noise
sources.description: IID Beta(0.3, 0.3) noise --- U-shaped distribution concentrating mass at both extremes with a valley in the middle, structurally opposite to Gaussian

sources.name: Zipf Distribution
sources.description: IID draws from Zipf/power-law distribution --- steep rank-frequency, heavy right tail

sources.name: Benford's Law
sources.description: Benford-distributed significands --- leading-digit law P(d) = log₁₀(1+1/d), the distribution of first digits in real-world datasets spanning multiple orders of magnitude

sources.name: Noisy Period-2
sources.description: Period-2 oscillation corrupted by additive noise --- deterministic alternation partially washed out by Gaussian perturbation, bridging periodic and stochastic regimes

sources.name: Intermittent Silence
sources.description: Signal with long silent stretches punctuated by active bursts --- on/off intermittency

sources.name: Hawkes Process
sources.description: Self-exciting point process --- events trigger more events, creating clustered bursts

sources.name: Multiplicative Cascade
sources.description: Random multiplicative process on dyadic tree --- multifractal burstiness at all scales

sources.name: Spike Train
sources.description: Integrate-and-fire neuron model --- quiescent charging with sudden discharge spikes

sources.name: GOE Spacings
sources.description: Gaussian Orthogonal Ensemble spacings --- linear repulsion P(s)~s exp(-πs²/4), time-reversal symmetric

sources.name: Quantum Walk
sources.description: Hadamard walk on Z --- ballistic spreading (σ~t not √t), interference creates asymmetric peaks

sources.name: Kicked Rotor
sources.description: Quantum kicked rotor --- dynamical localization freezes classical chaos, Anderson localization in momentum space

sources.name: Berry Random Wave

sources.name: Wigner Semicircle

sources.name: Entanglement Entropy
sources.description: Page curve entanglement entropy of random bipartite states --- ⟨S⟩ ≈ log(d_A) - d_A/(2d_B)

sources.name: Poisson Spacings
sources.description: Uncorrelated Poisson spacings P(s)=exp(-s) --- integrable quantum systems, no level repulsion

pc1.description: Uniform / high entropy at low end; Structured / peaked at high end

geometry_catalog.name: E8 Lattice
geometry_catalog.description: Projects 8-byte windows onto the 240 roots of E8, the densest lattice sphere-packing in 8 dimensions. Root usage diversity and alignment measure algebraic constraint.
geometry_catalog.detects: Lattice alignment, algebraic constraint

geometry_catalog.name: G2 Root System
geometry_catalog.description: Projects byte pairs onto the 12 roots of G2. Detects hexagonal symmetry in consecutive-byte correlations.
geometry_catalog.detects: Hexagonal byte-pair symmetry

geometry_catalog.name: D4 Triality
geometry_catalog.description: Projects 4-byte windows onto the 24 roots of D4 and measures triality invariance — the unique order-3 symmetry of Spin(8).
geometry_catalog.detects: Triality symmetry, 4-byte structural constraint

geometry_catalog.name: H3 Icosahedral
geometry_catalog.description: Projects 3-byte windows onto the 30 roots of H3 (icosidodecahedron vertices). Detects non-crystallographic 5-fold symmetry.
geometry_catalog.detects: Icosahedral symmetry, 5-fold rotational order

geometry_catalog.name: H4 600-Cell
geometry_catalog.description: Projects 4-byte windows onto the 120 roots of H4 (600-cell vertices). Detects non-crystallographic symmetry in 4D.
geometry_catalog.detects: 600-cell alignment, non-crystallographic 4D symmetry

geometry_catalog.name: Torus T^2
geometry_catalog.description: Maps consecutive byte pairs to a flat torus (quotient R^2/Z^2). Coverage and nearest-neighbor distance reveal periodic or constrained structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Periodicity, cyclic coverage, uniformity

geometry_catalog.name: Hyperbolic (Poincaré)
geometry_catalog.description: Embeds data in the Poincare disk, where distances grow exponentially near the boundary. Hierarchical or tree-like data clusters near the edge.
geometry_catalog.detects: Hierarchy depth, branching, boundary clustering

geometry_catalog.name: Heisenberg (Nil) (centered)
geometry_catalog.description: Lifts byte pairs to the 3D Heisenberg group, where the z-coordinate accumulates signed area (xy cross-products). Correlated data twists the path; uncorrelated data stays flat.
geometry_catalog.detects: Correlation twist, phase coupling, area accumulation

geometry_catalog.name: Spherical S²
geometry_catalog.description: Maps byte triples to the 2-sphere via spherical coordinates. Measures directional concentration, hemisphere balance, and angular spread.
geometry_catalog.detects: Directional clustering, angular uniformity

geometry_catalog.name: Sol (Thurston)
geometry_catalog.description: One of Thurston's eight 3D geometries. The Sol metric stretches one direction exponentially while contracting the other, detecting anisotropic scaling.
geometry_catalog.detects: Hyperbolic splitting, exponential divergence

geometry_catalog.name: S² × ℝ (Thurston)
geometry_catalog.description: Thurston geometry: product of the 2-sphere and the real line. Detects data with layered spherical structure — directional concentration that drifts over time.
geometry_catalog.detects: Spherical layering, radial drift

geometry_catalog.name: Cantor Set
geometry_catalog.description: Interprets bits as a base-3 address into the Cantor set. Gap structure and dust fraction measure self-similarity in the ternary digit stream.
geometry_catalog.detects: Gaps, dust fraction, ternary self-similarity

geometry_catalog.name: H² × ℝ (Thurston)
geometry_catalog.description: Thurston geometry: product of the hyperbolic plane and the real line. Combines hierarchical depth (hyperbolic) with vertical drift (Euclidean).
geometry_catalog.detects: Hyperbolic layering, vertical drift

geometry_catalog.name: SL(2,ℝ) (Thurston)
geometry_catalog.description: Thurston geometry: the universal cover of the unit tangent bundle of H^2. Accumulates 2x2 matrices and classifies the path as elliptic, parabolic, or hyperbolic by trace.
geometry_catalog.detects: Shear flow, geodesic divergence, rotation-shear coupling

geometry_catalog.name: 2-adic
geometry_catalog.description: Measures distances via 2-adic valuation: two bytes are close if they agree on many trailing bits. Ultrametric violations reveal non-hierarchical structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: p-adic clustering, divisibility depth, modular structure

geometry_catalog.name: Tropical
geometry_catalog.description: Tropical algebra replaces (add,multiply) with (min,add). The resulting piecewise-linear envelope reveals slope transitions and regime boundaries.
geometry_catalog.detects: Piecewise-linear regimes, slope diversity, envelope structure

geometry_catalog.name: Projective ℙ²
geometry_catalog.description: Lifts byte triples to projective 2-space (homogeneous coordinates). Cross-ratio variance measures departure from projective invariance.
geometry_catalog.detects: Scale invariance, cross-ratio stability, projective curvature

geometry_catalog.name: Wasserstein
geometry_catalog.description: Computes optimal transport (earth mover's) distance between windowed histograms. Self-similarity and concentration measure distributional stability.
geometry_catalog.detects: Distribution shape, transport cost, self-similarity

geometry_catalog.name: Fisher Information
geometry_catalog.description: Treats windowed histograms as points on a statistical manifold. The Fisher metric measures how sharply the distribution changes — high curvature means the data is informationally rich.
geometry_catalog.detects: Information gradient, statistical curvature, parameter sensitivity

geometry_catalog.name: Persistent Homology
geometry_catalog.description: Builds a Vietoris-Rips filtration on delay-embedded points. Persistent features (connected components H0, loops H1) that survive across scales indicate robust topological structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Holes, loops, connected components, topological persistence

geometry_catalog.name: Lorentzian
geometry_catalog.description: Treats consecutive (time, value) pairs as events in 1+1 Minkowski spacetime. Classifies intervals as timelike, spacelike, or lightlike to detect causal structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Causal ordering, lightcone structure, timelike fraction

geometry_catalog.name: Symplectic
geometry_catalog.description: Constructs a phase portrait (position vs. momentum) from the time series. The symplectic area form measures trajectory stationarity and return structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Phase space area, trajectory stationarity, recurrence

geometry_catalog.name: Logarithmic Spiral
geometry_catalog.description: Maps the time series to a logarithmic spiral in polar coordinates. Growth rate, winding number, and angular uniformity measure multiplicative structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Growth rate, spiral tightness, radial regularity

geometry_catalog.name: Penrose (Quasicrystal)
geometry_catalog.description: Projects the 1D signal into a 2D diffraction pattern and tests for fivefold Bragg peaks, the hallmark of Penrose quasicrystalline order.
geometry_catalog.detects: Fivefold diffraction symmetry, Bragg peak contrast, aperiodic order

geometry_catalog.name: Ammann-Beenker (Octagonal)
geometry_catalog.description: Tests for eightfold quasicrystalline order (the Ammann-Beenker tiling). Measures cardinal vs. diagonal anisotropy in the diffraction pattern.
geometry_catalog.detects: Eightfold diffraction symmetry, Bragg peak contrast, cardinal-diagonal anisotropy

geometry_catalog.name: Einstein (Hat Monotile)
geometry_catalog.description: Correlates the signal with the Hat monotile boundary kernel (Smith et al., 2023). Detects the aperiodic tiling's distinctive chiral hexagonal structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Hat motif correlation, tortuosity self-similarity, chirality

geometry_catalog.name: Dodecagonal (Stampfli)
geometry_catalog.description: Tests for 12-fold quasicrystalline order (Stampfli square-triangle tiling, ratio 2+sqrt(3)). Found in Ta-Te and V-Ni-Si alloys.
geometry_catalog.detects: Twelvefold diffraction symmetry, square-triangle tiling order

geometry_catalog.name: Decagonal (Al-Ni-Co)
geometry_catalog.description: Tests for 10-fold quasicrystalline order via Golden Ratio spacing. Decagonal quasicrystals (Al-Ni-Co) are periodic in one axis, aperiodic in the other two.
geometry_catalog.detects: Tenfold diffraction symmetry, Golden Mean scaling

geometry_catalog.name: Septagonal (Danzer)
geometry_catalog.description: Tests for 7-fold quasicrystalline order (Danzer tiling). Sevenfold symmetry is crystallographically forbidden, arising only in aperiodic structures.
geometry_catalog.detects: Sevenfold diffraction symmetry, Danzer tiling order

geometry_catalog.name: Fractal (Mandelbrot)
geometry_catalog.description: Uses byte pairs as starting points z0 for Mandelbrot iteration z -> z^2 + c. Escape times and orbit statistics measure fractal boundary structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Escape rate, fractal dimension, boundary complexity

geometry_catalog.name: Julia Set
geometry_catalog.description: Fixed Julia set parameter c acts as a tunable sensor. Data values become starting points z0; escape time and orbit stability detect dynamical trapping.
geometry_catalog.detects: Dynamical trapping, basin structure, Julia dimension

geometry_catalog.name: Higher-Order Statistics
geometry_catalog.description: Computes windowed skewness, kurtosis, permutation entropy, and bispectral coherence — the statistical fingerprint beyond mean and variance.
geometry_catalog.detects: Skewness, kurtosis, tail asymmetry, non-Gaussianity

geometry_catalog.name: Hölder Regularity
geometry_catalog.description: Estimates pointwise Holder exponents via wavelet leaders. The regularity spectrum (multifractal formalism) measures local smoothness variation.
geometry_catalog.detects: Local roughness, regularity spectrum, singularity strength

geometry_catalog.name: p-Variation
geometry_catalog.description: Computes the p-th variation (sum of |increments|^p) for multiple p. The critical p where variation transitions from finite to infinite characterizes path roughness.
geometry_catalog.detects: Path roughness, variation index, regularity

geometry_catalog.name: Multi-Scale Wasserstein
geometry_catalog.description: Computes Wasserstein distances between histograms at multiple coarsening scales. Scale coherence reveals distributional self-similarity.
geometry_catalog.detects: Scale coherence, distributional drift, self-similarity

geometry_catalog.name: Spectral Analysis
geometry_catalog.description: FFT power spectrum analysis: spectral slope (1/f^beta exponent), entropy, flatness, centroid, and bandwidth characterize the frequency content.
geometry_catalog.detects: Dominant frequency, spectral slope, bandwidth, periodicity

geometry_catalog.name: Information Theory
geometry_catalog.description: Block entropies at multiple depths (1, 2, 4 bytes), entropy rate, compression ratio, and mutual information at lag 1 and 8. Measures sequential redundancy.
geometry_catalog.detects: Shannon entropy, complexity, redundancy

geometry_catalog.name: Recurrence Quantification
geometry_catalog.description: Recurrence quantification analysis (RQA) on a delay-embedded phase portrait. Determinism, laminarity, and trapping time distinguish chaos from noise.
geometry_catalog.detects: Recurrence rate, determinism, laminarity, trapping time

geometry_catalog.name: Visibility Graph
geometry_catalog.description: Converts the time series to a graph: two points are connected if no intermediate value blocks the line of sight. Degree distribution and clustering reveal dynamical class.
geometry_catalog.detects: Graph degree distribution, clustering, small-worldness

geometry_catalog.name: Zipf–Mandelbrot (8-bit)
geometry_catalog.description: Treats N-bit sequences as symbols and fits Zipf-Mandelbrot frequency decay f(r) ~ (r+q)^-alpha. Vocabulary richness, hapax ratio, and Gini coefficient measure symbolic diversity.
geometry_catalog.detects: Zipf exponent, vocabulary richness, frequency decay

geometry_catalog.name: Zipf–Mandelbrot (16-bit)
geometry_catalog.description: Treats N-bit sequences as symbols and fits Zipf-Mandelbrot frequency decay f(r) ~ (r+q)^-alpha. Vocabulary richness, hapax ratio, and Gini coefficient measure symbolic diversity.
geometry_catalog.detects: Zipf exponent, vocabulary richness, frequency decay

geometry_catalog.name: Multifractal Spectrum
geometry_catalog.description: Estimates the multifractal singularity spectrum f(alpha) via structure functions. Spectrum width measures scaling heterogeneity — monofractal vs. rich multiscale structure.
geometry_catalog.detects: Spectrum width, dominant singularity, scaling nonlinearity

geometry_catalog.name: Predictability
geometry_catalog.description: Measures conditional entropy at increasing history depths (1, 2, 4, 8 bytes). The decay rate quantifies memory — fast decay means unpredictable, slow decay means structured.
geometry_catalog.detects: Conditional entropy, memory depth, sample entropy

geometry_catalog.name: Attractor Reconstruction
geometry_catalog.description: Delay-embedding reconstruction of the phase space attractor. Grassberger-Procaccia correlation dimension and maximum Lyapunov exponent distinguish chaos from noise.
geometry_catalog.detects: Correlation dimension, Lyapunov exponent, attractor filling
